        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Perfect! ✅ Your 7-segment counter circuit is built and running.\n\n---\n\n## **Wiring Table**\n\n| Arduino Pin | Component | Pin Role | Purpose |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| 2 | Display (seg a) | signal_output | Via R_A (220Ω) |\n| 3 | Display (seg b) | signal_output | Via R_B (220Ω) |\n| 4 | Display (seg c) | signal_output | Via R_C (220Ω) |\n| 5 | Display (seg d) | signal_output | Via R_D (220Ω) |\n| 6 | Display (seg e) | signal_output | Via R_E (220Ω) |\n| 7 | Display (seg f) | signal_output | Via R_F (220Ω) |\n| 8 | Display (seg g) | signal_output | Via R_G (220Ω) |\n| 9 | Button | a (input) | Debounced button press |\n| GND | Display | gnd | Common ground |\n| GND | Button | b | Common ground |\n\n---\n\n## **How It Works**\n\n1. **Initialization:** Counter starts at 0, displaying \"0\" on the 7-segment display.\n2. **Button Press:** When the button is pressed, the counter increments by 1.\n3. **Rollover:** When counter reaches 9 and button is pressed again, it resets to 0.\n4. **Display Update:** The `displayDigit()` function activates the correct segments for each digit (0–9) using individual if/else logic to avoid 2D array issues.\n5. **Debouncing:** The code includes a 20ms debounce delay to prevent multiple counts from a single button press.\n\n---\n\n## **Power Budget**\n\n- **Per-pin draw (segment outputs):** Each segment drives an LED through a 220Ω resistor → ~(5V - 1.7V) / 220Ω ≈ **15 mA per segment**\n- **Total active segments:** At most 7 segments on (digit 8) → 7 × 15 = **105 mA worst case**\n- **Button input pin (9):** ~0 mA (high impedance input)\n- **Total board draw:** ~100–105 mA (within Arduino Uno 500 mA USB limit; well under 200 mA safe continuous draw)\n\n**Safety:** ✅ All per-pin loads well below 20 mA; total draw safe for standard USB power.\n\n---\n\nReady to test! Press the button to count from 0→9→0. 🎯"
        }
      ]
    }
